# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: forcing-set-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In mathematics, the **axiom of choice**, abbreviated **AC** or **AoC**, is an axiom of set theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Informally put, the axiom of choice says that given any collection of non-empty sets, one can identify another set containing one element chosen from each set, even if the collection is infinite.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Formally, the axiom establishes existence rather than a construction; it states that for every set I and every I -indexed family $(S_{i})_{i\in I}$ of nonempty sets, there exists an I -indexed set $(x_{i})_{i\in I}$ of elements of $\cup _{i\in I}S_{i}$ such that $x_{i}\in S_{i}$ for every $i\in I$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The axiom of choice was formulated in 1904 by Ernst Zermelo in order to formalize his proof of the well-ordering theorem.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] An illustrative example is sets picked from the natural numbers.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] From such sets, one may always select the smallest number, e.g. given the sets {{4, 5, 6}, {10, 12}, {1, 400, 617, 8000}}, the set containing each smallest element is {4, 10, 1}.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In this case, "select the smallest number" is a choice function.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Even if infinitely many sets are collected from the natural numbers, it will always be possible to form a choice function from choosing the smallest element from each set to produce a set; the axiom of choice is not needed here.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] On the other hand, for the collection of all non-empty subsets of the real numbers, there is *no* known *canonical* rule by which one can choose one element from each of these subsets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In that case, the axiom of choice must be invoked to construct the desired choice function.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Bertrand Russell coined an analogy: for any (even infinite) collection of unordered pairs of shoes, one can pick out the left shoe from each pair to obtain an appropriate collection (i.e. set) of shoes; this makes it possible to define a choice function without using the axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Although originally controversial, the axiom of choice is now used without reservation by most mathematicians, and is included in the standard form of axiomatic set theory, Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory with the axiom of choice (ZFC).
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] One motivation for this is that a number of generally accepted mathematical results, such as Tychonoff's theorem, require the axiom of choice for their proofs.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Contemporary set theorists also study axioms that are not compatible with the axiom of choice, such as the axiom of determinacy.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] While some varieties of constructive mathematics avoid the axiom of choice, others embrace it.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] A choice function (also called selector or selection) is a function f , defined on a collection X of nonempty sets, such that for every set A in X , $f(A)$ is an element of A .
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Each choice function on a family X of nonempty sets is an element of the Cartesian product of the sets in X , and vice versa.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The Cartesian product of any collection of nonempty sets is nonempty.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] This form implies a more general form where the Cartesian product is of a general indexed family of sets (which may contain duplicates), since one can always select the same element from duplicate factors.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] There are many other equivalent statements of the axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] These are equivalent in the sense that, in the presence of other basic axioms of set theory, they imply the axiom of choice and are implied by it.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Note that $P\lor Q\lor R$ is logically equivalent to $(\lnot P\land \lnot Q)\implies R$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] This guarantees for any partition of a set X the existence of a subset C of X containing exactly one element from each part of the partition.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] (with the empty set removed) has a choice function.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Authors who use this formulation often speak of the *choice function on A*, but this is a slightly different notion of choice function.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Its domain is the power set of A (with the empty set removed), and so makes sense for any set A , whereas with the definition used elsewhere in this article, the domain of a choice function on a *collection of sets* is that collection, and so only makes sense for sets of sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Until the late 19th century, the axiom of choice was often used implicitly, although it had not yet been formally stated.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, after having established that the set *X* contains only non-empty sets, a mathematician might have said "let *F*(*s*) be one of the members of *s* for all *s* in *X*" to define a function *F*.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In general, it is impossible to prove that *F* exists without the axiom of choice, but this seems to have gone unnoticed until Zermelo.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The existence of a choice function for a finite collection of nonempty sets can be proved by the principle of finite induction, without appealing to the axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The proof uses the fact that, given a *single* nonempty set ⁠ A ⁠, first-order logic allows choosing some concrete ⁠ $a\in A$ ⁠.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] However, since a proof in first-order logic must be finite, one cannot make an infinite number of choices with first-order logic alone.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Another case where the axiom of choice is not needed is when there exists an explicit rule that gives a *canonical* choice function.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, if each member of the collection ⁠ X ⁠ is a nonempty subset of the natural numbers, then one such explicit rule is to choose the *smallest element* of each ⁠ $A\in X$ ⁠.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The canonical choice function that maps each ⁠ $A\in X$ ⁠ to its smallest element can again be constructed in ZF without the axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In general, if the union of all sets in ⁠ X ⁠ can be well-ordered, then a choice function for ⁠ X ⁠ can be constructed without using the axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Note that it does not suffice that each ⁠ $A\in X$ ⁠ can be well-ordered, since the axiom of choice may be needed to choose a *canonical well-ordering* for each ⁠ A ⁠ anyway.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] As an example where the axiom of choice is required, let ⁠ X ⁠ be set of all non-empty subsets of the real numbers.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Choosing the least element from each set no longer works, because some subsets of the real numbers do not have least elements.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, the open interval ⁠ $(0,1)$ ⁠ does not have a least element: if ⁠ x ⁠ is in ⁠ $(0,1)$ ⁠, then so is ⁠ $x/2$ ⁠, and ⁠ $x/2$ ⁠ is always strictly smaller than ⁠ x ⁠.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] This strategy fails here because the natural order of real numbers is not a well-order.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] If there exists a different ordering of the real numbers which is a well-ordering, then applying the least-element strategy with respect to that ordering would give a choice function for ⁠ X ⁠.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Conversely, if there exists a choice function for ⁠ X ⁠, then the proof of the well-ordering theorem would show that a well-ordering of the real numbers does exist.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Let ⁠ S ⁠ be the unit circle, and ⁠ G ⁠ be the group consisting of all rational rotations (i.e., rotations by angles which are rational multiples of ⁠ $\pi$ ⁠).
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Since ⁠ G ⁠ is countable while ⁠ S ⁠ is uncountable, ⁠ S ⁠ must break up into uncountably many orbits under the action of ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Using the axiom of choice, we could pick a single point from each orbit, obtaining an uncountable subset ⁠ X ⁠ of ⁠ S ⁠ with the property that all of its translates by ⁠ G ⁠ are disjoint from ⁠ X ⁠.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The set of those translates partitions the circle into a countable collection of pairwise disjoint sets, which are all pairwise congruent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The set ⁠ X ⁠ will be non-measurable for any rotation-invariant countably additive measure on ⁠ S ⁠: if ⁠ X ⁠ has zero measure, countable additivity would imply that the whole circle has zero measure.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] If ⁠ X ⁠ has positive measure, countable additivity would show that the circle has infinite measure.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Applying a similar construction to the three-dimensional ball can result in a set that is non-measurable even for any rotation-invariant *finitely* additive measure, as shown by the Banach–Tarski paradox.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] A proof requiring the axiom of choice may establish the existence of an object without *canonically* defining the object in the language of set theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, while the axiom of choice implies that there is a well-ordering of the real numbers, there are models of set theory with the axiom of choice in which no individual well-ordering of the reals is definable.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Similarly, although a subset of the real numbers that is not Lebesgue measurable can be proved to exist using the axiom of choice, it is consistent that no such set is definable.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The axiom of choice asserts the existence of these intangibles (objects that are proved to exist, but which cannot be constructed in any *canonical* way), which may conflict with some philosophical principles.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Because there is no canonical well-ordering of all sets, a construction that relies on a well-ordering may not produce a canonical result, even if a canonical result is desired (as is often the case in category theory).
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] This has been used as an argument against the use of the axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Another argument against the axiom of choice is that it implies the existence of objects that may seem counterintuitive.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] One example is the Banach–Tarski paradox, which says that it is possible to decompose the 3-dimensional solid unit ball into finitely many pieces and, using only rotations and translations, reassemble the pieces into two solid balls each with the same volume as the original.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The pieces in this decomposition, constructed using the axiom of choice, are non-measurable sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Despite these seemingly paradoxical results, most mathematicians accept the axiom of choice as a valid principle for proving new results in mathematics.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Theorems of ZF hold true in any model of that theory, regardless of the truth or falsity of the axiom of choice in that particular model.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The implications of choice below, including weaker versions of the axiom itself, are listed because they are not theorems of ZF.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The Banach–Tarski paradox, for example, is neither provable nor disprovable from ZF alone: it is impossible to construct the required decomposition of the unit ball in ZF, but also impossible to prove there is no such decomposition.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Such statements can be rephrased as conditional statements—for example, "If AC holds, then the decomposition in the Banach–Tarski paradox exists." Such conditional statements are provable in ZF when the original statements are provable from ZF and the axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] As discussed above, in the classical theory of ZFC, the axiom of choice enables nonconstructive proofs in which the existence of a type of object is proved without an explicit canonical construction of an instance of this type.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In fact, in set theory and topos theory, Diaconescu's theorem shows that the axiom of choice implies the law of excluded middle.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The principle is thus not available in constructive set theory, where non-classical logic is employed.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The situation is different when the principle is formulated in Martin-Löf type theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] There and higher-order Heyting arithmetic, the appropriate statement of the axiom of choice is (depending on approach) included as an axiom or provable as a theorem.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] A cause for this difference is that the axiom of choice in type theory does not have the extensionality properties that the axiom of choice in constructive set theory does.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The type theoretical context is discussed further below.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Different choice principles have been thoroughly studied in the constructive contexts and the principles' status varies between different school and varieties of the constructive mathematics.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Some results in constructive set theory use the axiom of countable choice or the axiom of dependent choice, which do not imply the law of the excluded middle.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Although the axiom of countable choice in particular is commonly used in constructive mathematics, its use has also been questioned.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] It has been known since as early as 1922 that the axiom of choice may fail in a variant of ZF with urelements, through the technique of permutation models introduced by Abraham Fraenkel and developed further by Andrzej Mostowski.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The basic technique can be illustrated as follows: Let *x**n* and *y**n* be distinct urelements for *n*=1, 2, 3..., and build a model where each set is symmetric under the interchange *x**n* ↔ *y**n* for all but a finite number of *n*.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In 1938, Kurt Gödel showed that the *negation* of the axiom of choice is not a theorem of ZF by constructing an inner model (the constructible universe) that satisfies ZFC, thus showing that ZFC is consistent if ZF itself is consistent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In 1963, Paul Cohen employed the technique of forcing, developed for this purpose, to show that, assuming ZF is consistent, the axiom of choice itself is not a theorem of ZF.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] He did this by constructing a much more complex model that satisfies ZF¬C (ZF with the negation of AC added as axiom) and thus showing that ZF¬C is consistent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Cohen's model is a symmetric model, which is similar to permutation models, but uses "generic" subsets of the natural numbers (justified by forcing) in place of urelements.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Together these results establish that the axiom of choice is logically independent of ZF.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The assumption that ZF is consistent is harmless because adding another axiom to an already inconsistent system cannot make the situation worse.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Because of independence, the decision whether to use the axiom of choice (or its negation) in a proof cannot be made by appeal to other axioms of set theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] One argument in favor of using the axiom of choice is that it is convenient because it allows one to prove some simplifying propositions that otherwise could not be proved.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Frequently, the axiom of choice allows generalizing a theorem to "larger" objects.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, it is provable without the axiom of choice that every vector space of finite dimension has a basis, but the generalization to all vector spaces requires the axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Likewise, a finite product of compact spaces can be proven to be compact without the axiom of choice, but the generalization to infinite products (Tychonoff's theorem) requires the axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The proof of the independence result also shows that a wide class of mathematical statements, including all statements that can be phrased in the language of Peano arithmetic, are provable in ZF if and only if they are provable in ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Statements in this class include the statement that P = NP, the Riemann hypothesis, and many other unsolved mathematical problems.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] When attempting to solve problems in this class, it makes no difference whether ZF or ZFC is employed if the only question is the existence of a proof.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] It is possible, however, that there is a shorter proof of a theorem from ZFC than from ZF.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The axiom of choice is not the only significant statement that is independent of ZF.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, the generalized continuum hypothesis (GCH) is not only independent of ZF, but also independent of ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] However, ZF plus GCH implies AC, making GCH a strictly stronger claim than AC, even though they are both independent of ZF.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The axiom of constructibility and the generalized continuum hypothesis each imply the axiom of choice and are strictly stronger than it.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In class theories such as Von Neumann–Bernays–Gödel set theory and Morse–Kelley set theory, there is an axiom called the axiom of global choice that is stronger than the axiom of choice for sets because it also applies to proper classes.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The axiom of global choice follows from the axiom of limitation of size.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Tarski's axiom, which is used in Tarski–Grothendieck set theory and states (in the vernacular) that every set belongs to *some* Grothendieck universe, is stronger than the axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] There are important statements that, assuming the axioms of ZF but neither AC nor ¬AC, are equivalent to the axiom of choice (that is, their truth values in ZF, while undecidable, are the same as that of AC).
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The most important among them are Zorn's lemma and the well-ordering theorem.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In fact, Zermelo initially introduced the axiom of choice in order to formalize his proof of the well-ordering theorem.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Several results in category theory invoke the axiom of choice for their proof.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] These results might be weaker than, equivalent to, or stronger than the axiom of choice, depending on the strength of the technical foundations.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, if one defines categories in terms of sets, that is, as sets of objects and morphisms (usually called a small category), then there is no category of all sets, and so it is difficult for a category-theoretic formulation to apply to all sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] On the other hand, other foundational descriptions of category theory are considerably stronger, and an identical category-theoretic statement of choice may be stronger than the standard formulation, à la class theory, mentioned above.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] There are several weaker statements unprovable in ZF that are logically implied by the axiom of choice (AC) within ZF but are not equivalent to AC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] One example is the axiom of dependent choice (DC).
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] A still weaker example is the axiom of countable choice (ACω or CC), which states that a choice function exists for any countable family of nonempty sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] These axioms are sufficient for many proofs in elementary mathematical analysis, and are consistent with some principles, such as the Lebesgue measurability of all subsets of real numbers, that are disprovable from the full axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Given an ordinal parameter α ≥ ω+2 – for every set *S* with rank less than α, *S* is well-orderable.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Given an ordinal parameter α ≥ 1 – for every set *S* with Hartogs number less than ωα, *S* is well-orderable.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] As the ordinal parameter is increased, these approximate the full axiom of choice more and more closely.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Other choice axioms weaker than axiom of choice include the Boolean prime ideal theorem and the axiom of uniformization.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The former is equivalent in ZF to Tarski's 1930 ultrafilter lemma: every filter is a subset of some ultrafilter.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] One of the most interesting aspects of the axiom of choice is the large number of places in mathematics where it shows up.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Here are some statements that require the axiom of choice in the sense that they are not provable from ZF but are provable from ZFC (ZF plus AC).
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Equivalently, these statements are true in all models of ZFC but false in some models of ZF.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Does the partition principle imply the axiom of choice?
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] There are several historically important set-theoretic statements implied by AC whose equivalence to AC is open.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Zermelo cited the partition principle, which was formulated before AC itself, as a justification for believing AC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In 1906, Russell declared PP to be equivalent, but whether the partition principle implies AC is an old open problem in set theory, and the equivalences of the other statements are similarly hard old open problems.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In every *known* model of ZF where choice fails, these statements fail too, but it is unknown whether they can hold without choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] If we abbreviate by BP the claim that every set of real numbers has the property of Baire, then BP is stronger than ¬AC, which asserts the nonexistence of any choice function on perhaps only a single set of nonempty sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Strengthened negations may be compatible with weakened forms of AC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, ZF + DC + BP is consistent, if ZF is.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] It is also consistent with ZF + DC that every set of reals is Lebesgue measurable, but this consistency result, due to Robert M.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Solovay, cannot be proved in ZFC itself, but requires a mild large cardinal assumption (the existence of an inaccessible cardinal).
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The much stronger axiom of determinacy, or AD, implies that every set of reals is Lebesgue measurable, has the property of Baire, and has the perfect set property (all three of these results are refuted by AC itself).
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] ZF + DC + AD is consistent provided that a sufficiently strong large cardinal axiom is consistent (the existence of infinitely many Woodin cardinals).
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Quine's system of axiomatic set theory, New Foundations (NF), takes its name from the title ("New Foundations for Mathematical Logic") of the 1937 article that introduced it.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In the NF axiomatic system, the axiom of choice can be disproved.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] There are models of Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory in which the axiom of choice is false.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] We shall abbreviate "Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory plus the negation of the axiom of choice" by ZF¬C.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For certain models of ZF¬C, it is possible to validate the negation of some standard ZFC theorems.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] As any model of ZF¬C is also a model of ZF, it is the case that for each of the following statements, there exists a model of ZF in which that statement is true.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Additionally, by imposing definability conditions on sets (in the sense of descriptive set theory) one can often prove restricted versions of the axiom of choice from axioms incompatible with general choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] This appears, for example, in the Moschovakis coding lemma.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In type theory, a different kind of statement is known as the axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] This form begins with two types, σ and τ, and a relation *R* between objects of type σ and objects of type τ.
[src:forcing-set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Unlike in set theory, the axiom of choice in type theory is typically stated as an axiom scheme, in which *R* varies over all formulas or over all formulas of a particular logical form.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] In mathematics, in set theory, the **constructible universe** (or **Gödel's constructible universe**), denoted by $L,$ is a particular class of sets that can be described entirely in terms of simpler sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] L is the union of the **constructible hierarchy** $L_{\alpha }$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] It was introduced by Kurt Gödel in his 1938 paper "The Consistency of the Axiom of Choice and of the Generalized Continuum-Hypothesis".
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] In this paper, he proved that the constructible universe is an inner model of ZF set theory (that is, of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory with the axiom of choice excluded), and also that the axiom of choice and the generalized continuum hypothesis are true in the constructible universe.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] This shows that both propositions are consistent with the basic axioms of set theory, if ZF itself is consistent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Since many other theorems only hold in systems in which one or both of the propositions is true, their consistency is an important result.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] L can be thought of as being built in "stages" resembling the construction of the von Neumann universe, V .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] In von Neumann's universe, at a successor stage, one takes $V_{\alpha +1}$ to be the set of *all* subsets of the previous stage, $V_{\alpha }$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] By limiting oneself to sets defined only in terms of what has already been constructed, one ensures that the resulting sets will be constructed in a way that is independent of the peculiarities of the surrounding model of set theory and contained in any such model.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] So $L_{\alpha }$ is a subset of $L_{\alpha +1}$ , which is a subset of the power set of $L_{\alpha }$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Consequently, this is a tower of nested transitive sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] The elements of L are called "constructible" sets; and L itself is the "constructible universe".
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] The "axiom of constructibility", sometimes denoted " $V=L$ ", says that every set (of V ) is constructible, i.e. in L .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] For any finite ordinal n , the sets $L_{n}$ and $V_{n}$ are the same (whether V equals L or not), and thus $L_{\omega }$ = $V_{\omega }$ : their elements are exactly the hereditarily finite sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Equality beyond this point does not hold.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Even in models of ZFC in which V equals L , $L_{\omega +1}$ is a proper subset of $V_{\omega +1}$ , and thereafter $L_{\alpha +1}$ is a proper subset of the power set of $L_{\alpha }$ for all $\alpha >\omega$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] On the other hand, $V=L$ does imply that $V_{\alpha }$ equals $L_{\alpha }$ if $\alpha =\omega _{\alpha }$ , for example if $\alpha$ is inaccessible.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] More generally, $V=L$ implies $H_{\alpha }$ = $L_{\alpha }$ for all infinite cardinals $\alpha$ , where $H_{\alpha }$ is the set of sets which are hereditarily of cardinality less than $\alpha$ (see hereditarily countable set#Generalizations).
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] If $\alpha$ is an infinite ordinal then there is a bijection between $L_{\alpha }$ and $\alpha$ , and the bijection is constructible.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] So these sets are equinumerous in any transitive model of set theory that includes them.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] As defined above, ${\textrm {Def}}(X)$ is the set of subsets of X defined by $\Delta _{0}$ formulas (with respect to the Lévy hierarchy, i.e., formulas of set theory containing only bounded quantifiers) that use as parameters only X and its elements.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Another definition, due to Gödel, characterizes each $L_{\alpha +1}$ as the intersection of the power set of $L_{\alpha }$ with the closure of $L_{\alpha }\cup \{L_{\alpha }\}$ under a collection of nine explicit functions, similar to Gödel operations.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] This definition makes no reference to definability.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] All arithmetical subsets of $\omega$ and relations on $\omega$ belong to $L_{\omega +1}$ (because the arithmetic definition gives one in $L_{\omega +1}$ ).
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Conversely, any subset of $\omega$ belonging to $L_{\omega +1}$ is arithmetical (because elements of $L_{\omega }$ can be coded by natural numbers in such a way that $\in$ is definable, i.e., arithmetic).
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] On the other hand, $L_{\omega +2}$ already contains certain non-arithmetical subsets of $\omega$ , such as the set of (natural numbers coding) true arithmetical statements (this can be defined from $L_{\omega +1}$ {\displaystyle } ({\displaystyle }) so it is in $L_{\omega +2}$ ).
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] All hyperarithmetical subsets of $\omega$ and relations on $\omega$ belong to $L_{\omega _{1}^{\mathrm {CK} }}$ (where $\omega _{1}^{\mathrm {CK} }$ stands for the Church–Kleene ordinal), and conversely any subset of $\omega$ that belongs to $L_{\omega _{1}^{\mathrm {CK} }}$ is hyperarithmetical.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] L is a transitive class and the interpretation uses the real element relationship, so it is well-founded.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] L is an inner model, i.e. it contains all the ordinal numbers of V and it has no "extra" sets beyond those in V .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] However L might be strictly a subclass of V .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] because we are using the same element relation and no new sets were added.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] by their definitions and by the rank they appear at.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Notice that the proof that L is a model of ZFC only requires that V be a model of ZF, i.e. we do *not* assume that the axiom of choice holds in V .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] If W is any standard model of ZF sharing the same ordinals as V , then the L defined in W is the same as the L defined in V .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] In particular, $L_{\alpha }$ is the same in W and V , for any ordinal $\alpha$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] And the same formulas and parameters in $\mathrm {Def} (L_{\alpha })$ produce the same constructible sets in $L_{\alpha +1}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Furthermore, since L is a subclass of V and, similarly, L is a subclass of W , L is the smallest class containing all the ordinals that is an inner model of ZF.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Indeed, L is the intersection of all such classes.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] If there is a *set* W in V that is an inner model of ZF, and the ordinal $\kappa$ is the set of ordinals that occur in W , then $L_{\kappa }$ is the L of W .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] If there is a set that is a standard model of ZF, then the smallest such set is such a $L_{\kappa }$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] This set is called the **minimal model** of ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Using the downward Löwenheim–Skolem theorem, one can show that the minimal model (if it exists) is a countable set.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Of course, any consistent theory must have a model, so even within the minimal model of set theory there are sets that are models of ZF (assuming ZF is consistent).
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] However, those set models are non-standard.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] In particular, they do not use the normal element relation and they are not well founded.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Because both " L constructed within L " and " V constructed within L " result in the real L , and both the L of $L_{\kappa }$ and the V of $L_{\kappa }$ are the real $L_{\kappa }$ , we get that $V=L$ is true in L and in any $L_{\kappa }$ that is a model of ZF.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] However, $V=L$ does not hold in any other standard model of ZF.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Since $\mathrm {Ord} \subset L\subseteq V$ , properties of ordinals that depend on the absence of a function or other structure (i.e. $\Pi _{1}^{\mathrm {ZF} }$ formulas) are preserved when going down from V to L .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Hence initial ordinals of cardinals remain initial in L .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Weak limit cardinals become strong limit cardinals in L because the generalized continuum hypothesis holds in L .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Weakly inaccessible cardinals become strongly inaccessible.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Weakly Mahlo cardinals become strongly Mahlo.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] And more generally, any large cardinal property weaker than 0# (see the list of large cardinal properties) will be retained in L .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] However, $0^{\sharp }$ is false in L even if true in V .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] So all the large cardinals whose existence implies $0^{\sharp }$ cease to have those large cardinal properties, but retain the properties weaker than $0^{\sharp }$ which they also possess.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] For example, measurable cardinals cease to be measurable but remain Mahlo in L .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] If $0^{\sharp }$ holds in V , then there is a closed unbounded class of ordinals that are order-indiscernible in L .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] While some of these are not even initial ordinals in V , they have all the large cardinal properties weaker than $0^{\sharp }$ in L .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Furthermore, any strictly increasing class function from this class of order-indiscernibles to itself can be extended in a unique way to an elementary embedding of L into L .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] This gives L a nice structure of repeating segments.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] There are various ways of well-ordering L .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Some of these involve the "fine structure" of L , which was first described by Ronald Bjorn Jensen in his 1972 paper entitled "The fine structure of the constructible hierarchy".
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Instead of explaining the fine structure, we will give an outline of how L could be well-ordered using only the definition given above.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Suppose x and y are two different sets in L and we wish to determine whether $x<y$ or $x>y$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] If x first appears in $L_{\alpha +1}$ and y first appears in $L_{\beta +1}$ and $\beta$ is different from $\alpha$ , then let $x<y$ if and only if $\alpha <\beta$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Henceforth, we suppose that $\beta =\alpha$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] The stage $L_{\alpha +1}=\mathrm {Def} (L_{\alpha })$ uses formulas with parameters from $L_{\alpha }$ to define the sets x and y .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] If one discounts (for the moment) the parameters, the formulas can be given a standard Gödel numbering by the natural numbers.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] If $\Phi$ is the formula with the smallest Gödel number that can be used to define x , and $\Psi$ is the formula with the smallest Gödel number that can be used to define y , and $\Psi$ is different from $\Phi$ , then let $x<y$ if and only if $\Phi <\Psi$ in the Gödel numbering.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Henceforth, we suppose that $\Psi =\Phi$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Suppose that $\Phi$ uses n parameters from $L_{\alpha }$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Suppose $z_{1},\ldots ,z_{n}$ is the sequence of parameters that can be used with $\Phi$ to define x , and $w_{1},\ldots ,w_{n}$ does the same for y .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] This is called the reverse lexicographic ordering; if there are multiple sequences of parameters that define one of the sets, we choose the least one under this ordering.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] It being understood that each parameter's possible values are ordered according to the restriction of the ordering of L to $L_{\alpha }$ , so this definition involves transfinite recursion on $\alpha$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] The well-ordering of the values of single parameters is provided by the inductive hypothesis of the transfinite induction.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] The values of n -tuples of parameters are well-ordered by the product ordering.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] The formulas with parameters are well-ordered by the ordered sum (by Gödel numbers) of well-orderings.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] And L is well-ordered by the ordered sum (indexed by $\alpha$ ) of the orderings on $L_{\alpha +1}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Notice that this well-ordering can be defined within L itself by a formula of set theory with no parameters, only the free-variables x and y .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] And this formula gives the same truth value regardless of whether it is evaluated in L , V , or W (some other standard model of ZF with the same ordinals) and we will suppose that the formula is false if either x or y is not in L .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] It is well known that the axiom of choice is equivalent to the ability to well-order every set.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Being able to well-order the proper class V (as we have done here with L ) is equivalent to the axiom of global choice, which is more powerful than the ordinary axiom of choice because it also covers proper classes of non-empty sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Proving that the axiom of separation, axiom of replacement, and axiom of choice hold in L requires (at least as shown above) the use of a reflection principle for L .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Let $S\in L_{\alpha }$ , and let T be any constructible subset of S .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Since $V=L$ is true in $L_{\beta }$ , it is also true in *K*, so $K=L_{\gamma }$ for some $\gamma$ having the same cardinal as $\alpha$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] And this in turn means that the "power set" of S has cardinal at most $\vert \delta \vert$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Assuming S itself has cardinal $\kappa$ , the "power set" must then have cardinal exactly $\kappa ^{+}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] But this is precisely the generalized continuum hypothesis relativized to L .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] There is a formula of set theory that expresses the idea that $X=L_{\alpha }$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] It has only free variables for X and $\alpha$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Using this we can expand the definition of each constructible set.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] This is equivalent to saying that: for all y , $y\in S$ if and only if [there exists X such that $X=L_{\alpha }$ and $y\in X$ and $\Psi (X,y,z_{1},\ldots ,z_{n})$ ] where $\Psi (X,\ldots )$ is the result of restricting each quantifier in $\Phi (\ldots )$ to X .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Notice that each $z_{k}\in L_{\beta +1}$ for some $\beta <\alpha$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Combine formulas for the z 's with the formula for S and apply existential quantifiers over the z 's outside and one gets a formula that defines the constructible set S using only the ordinals $\alpha$ that appear in expressions like $x=L_{\alpha }$ as parameters.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Example: The set $\{5,\omega \}$ is constructible.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Actually, even this complex formula has been simplified from what the instructions given in the first paragraph would yield.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] But the point remains, there is a formula of set theory that is true only for the desired constructible set S and that contains parameters only for ordinals.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Sometimes it is desirable to find a model of set theory that is narrow like L , but that includes or is influenced by a set that is not constructible.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] This gives rise to the concept of relative constructibility, of which there are two flavors, denoted by $L(A)$ and $L[A]$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] The class $L(A)$ for a non-constructible set A is the intersection of all classes that are standard models of set theory and contain A and all the ordinals.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] If $L(A)$ contains a well-ordering of the transitive closure of $\{A\}$ , then this can be extended to a well-ordering of $L(A)$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Otherwise, the axiom of choice will fail in $L(A)$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] A common example is $L(\mathbb {R} )$ , the smallest model that contains all the real numbers, which is used extensively in modern descriptive set theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] The class $L[A]$ is the class of sets whose construction is influenced by A , where A may be a (presumably non-constructible) set or a proper class.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] The definition of this class uses $\mathrm {Def} _{A}(X)$ , which is the same as $\mathrm {Def} (X)$ except instead of evaluating the truth of formulas $\Phi$ in the model $(X,\in )$ , one uses the model $(X,\in ,A)$ where A is a unary predicate.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] The intended interpretation of $A(y)$ is $y\in A$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Then the definition of $L[A]$ is exactly that of L only with $\mathrm {Def}$ replaced by $\mathrm {Def} _{A}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] $L[A]$ is always a model of the axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] Even if A is a set, A is not necessarily itself a member of $L[A]$ , although it always is if A is a set of ordinals.
[src:forcing-set-theory/constructible-universe] The sets in $L(A)$ or $L[A]$ are usually not actually constructible, and the properties of these models may be quite different from the properties of L itself.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In mathematics, specifically set theory, the **continuum hypothesis** (abbreviated **CH**) is a hypothesis about the possible sizes of infinite sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The name of the hypothesis comes from the term *continuum* for the real numbers.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory with the axiom of choice (ZFC), this is equivalent to the following equation in aleph numbers: $2^{\aleph _{0}}=\aleph _{1}$ , or even shorter with beth numbers: $\beth _{1}=\aleph _{1}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The continuum hypothesis was advanced by Georg Cantor in 1878.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] It became one of the most studied problems in set theory, and establishing its truth or falsehood was the first of Hilbert's 23 problems presented in 1900.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The answer to this problem is independent of ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] This means the axioms of ZFC can neither prove nor disprove the continuum hypothesis, meaning either the continuum hypothesis or its negation can be added as an axiom to ZFC set theory, with the resulting theory being consistent if and only if ZFC is consistent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] This independence was proved in 1963 by Paul Cohen, complementing earlier work by Kurt Gödel in 1940.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The **generalized continuum hypothesis** states that $\aleph _{\alpha +1}=2^{\aleph _{\alpha }}$ for every ordinal $\alpha$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The continuum hypothesis was first introduced by Georg Cantor in his 1878 paper "Ein Beitrag zur Mannigfaltigkeitslehre", in a form now called the weak continuum hypothesis which is equivalent to the standard formulation under the then-undeveloped axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cantor initially presented the weak continuum hypothesis as a theorem, but did not give a proof and later became uncertain of it.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] On 25 October 1882, Cantor wrote to his correspondent Gösta Mittag-Leffler, and formulated the continuum hypothesis (CH) in its modern form and gave his belief he could prove it.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] By the 1890s, many mathematicians in Germany and France were aware of the problem.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cantor tried for many years to prove CH but never succeeded.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] It became the first on David Hilbert's list of important open questions that was presented at the International Congress of Mathematicians (ICM) in the year 1900 in Paris.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] At that point, axiomatic set theory was not yet formulated.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Many erroneous proofs and disproofs of CH were given.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] As early as 1884, Paul Tannery claimed to prove CH, but the proof was erroneous.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In 1890, Beppo Levi claimed to have a proof from assuming that every subset of the real numbers has the Baire property, but no proof was ever published.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] At the 1904 ICM in Heidelberg, Gyula Kőnig announced he had disproven CH, drawing wide attention that even reached the Grand Duke of Baden Frederick I via Felix Klein, but a flaw in the proof was found the next day.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Felix Bernstein also published an attempted proof of CH in 1904, but it was wrong and attracted little response.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In 1926, Hilbert claimed to have solved the continuum hypothesis and gave a proof sketch, but this was also incorrect, although it influenced later ideas in recursion theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In 1906, Kőnig revised part of his attempted CH disproof and established Kőnig's theorem, which by using the concept of cofinality introduced in 1908 by Felix Hausdorff, shows that result that $2^{\aleph _{0}}$ cannot equal $\aleph _{\alpha }$ for $\alpha$ with cofinality $\omega$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Hausdorff formulated the question of whether $2^{\aleph _{\alpha }}=\aleph _{\alpha +1}$ for all ordinals $\alpha$ , which would be named the *generalized continuum hypothesis* by Alfred Tarski in 1925.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In 1923, Thoralf Skolem conjectured that CH could not be settled by the axioms of Zermelo set theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Kurt Gödel proved in 1940 that the negation of the continuum hypothesis, i.e., the existence of a set with intermediate cardinality, could not be proved in standard set theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The second half of the independence of the continuum hypothesis – i.e., unprovability of the nonexistence of an intermediate-sized set – was proved in 1963 by Paul Cohen.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Two sets are said to have the same *cardinality* or *cardinal number* if there exists a bijection (a one-to-one correspondence) between them.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Intuitively, for two sets S and T to have the same cardinality means that it is possible to "pair off" elements of S with elements of T in such a fashion that every element of S is paired off with exactly one element of T and vice versa.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Hence, the set $\{{\text{banana}},{\text{apple}},{\text{pear}}\}$ has the same cardinality as $\{{\text{yellow}},{\text{red}},{\text{green}}\}$ despite the sets themselves containing different elements.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] With infinite sets such as the set of integers or rational numbers, the existence of a bijection between two sets becomes more difficult to demonstrate.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] However, this intuitive analysis is flawed since it does not take into account the fact that all three sets are infinite.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Perhaps more importantly, it in fact conflates the concept of "size" of the set $\mathbb {Q}$ with the order or topological structure placed on it.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In fact, it turns out the rational numbers can actually be placed in one-to-one correspondence with the integers, and therefore the set of rational numbers is the same size (*cardinality*) as the set of integers: they are both countable sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cantor gave two proofs that the cardinality of the set of integers is strictly smaller than that of the set of real numbers (see Cantor's first uncountability proof and Cantor's diagonal argument).
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] His proofs, however, give no indication of the extent to which the cardinality of the integers is less than that of the real numbers.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cantor proposed the continuum hypothesis as a possible solution to this question.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In simple terms, the Continuum Hypothesis (CH) states that the set of real numbers has minimal possible cardinality which is greater than the cardinality of the set of integers.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] That is, every infinite set $S\subseteq \mathbb {R}$ of real numbers can either be mapped one-to-one into the integers or the real numbers can be mapped one-to-one into S .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Assuming the axiom of choice, there is a unique smallest cardinal number $\aleph _{1}$ greater than $\aleph _{0}$ , and the continuum hypothesis is in turn equivalent to the equality $2^{\aleph _{0}}=\aleph _{1}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The independence of the continuum hypothesis (CH) from Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory (ZF) follows from combined work of Kurt Gödel and Paul Cohen.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Gödel showed that CH cannot be disproved from ZF, even if the axiom of choice (AC) is adopted, i.e. from ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Gödel's proof shows that both CH and AC hold in the constructible universe L , an inner model of ZF set theory, assuming only the axioms of ZF.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The existence of an inner model of ZF in which additional axioms hold shows that the additional axioms are (relatively) consistent with ZF, provided ZF itself is consistent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The latter condition cannot be proved in ZF itself, due to Gödel's incompleteness theorems, but is widely believed to be true and can be proved in stronger set theories.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cohen showed that CH cannot be proven from the ZFC axioms, completing the overall independence proof.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] To prove his result, Cohen developed the method of forcing, which has become a standard tool in set theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Essentially, this method begins with a model of ZF in which CH holds and constructs another model which contains more sets than the original in a way that CH does not hold in the new model.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cohen was awarded the Fields Medal in 1966 for his proof.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cohen's independence proof shows that CH is independent of ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Further research has shown that CH is independent of all known *large cardinal axioms* in the context of ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Moreover, it has been shown that the cardinality of the continuum ${\mathfrak {c}}=2^{\aleph _{0}}$ can be any cardinal consistent with Kőnig's theorem.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] A result of Solovay, proved shortly after Cohen's result on the independence of the continuum hypothesis, shows that in any model of ZFC, if $\kappa$ is a cardinal of uncountable cofinality, then there is a forcing extension in which $2^{\aleph _{0}}=\kappa$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] However, per Kőnig's theorem, it is not consistent to assume $2^{\aleph _{0}}$ is $\aleph _{\omega }$ or $\aleph _{\omega _{1}+\omega }$ or any cardinal with cofinality $\omega$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The continuum hypothesis is closely related to many statements in analysis, point-set topology and measure theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] As a result of its independence, many substantial conjectures in those fields have subsequently been shown to be independent as well.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The independence from ZFC means that proving or disproving the CH within ZFC is impossible.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] However, Gödel and Cohen's negative results are not universally accepted as disposing of all interest in the continuum hypothesis.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The continuum hypothesis remains an active topic of research: see Woodin and Koellner for an overview of the current research status.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The continuum hypothesis and the axiom of choice were among the first genuinely mathematical statements shown to be independent of ZF set theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The latter independence result indeed holds for many theories.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Gödel believed that CH is false, and that his proof that CH is consistent with ZFC only shows that the Zermelo–Fraenkel axioms do not adequately characterize the universe of sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Gödel was a Platonist and therefore had no problems with asserting the truth and falsehood of statements independent of their provability.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cohen, though a formalist, also tended towards rejecting CH.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Historically, mathematicians who favored a "rich" and "large" universe of sets were against CH, while those favoring a "neat" and "controllable" universe favored CH.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Parallel arguments were made for and against the axiom of constructibility, which implies CH.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] More recently, Matthew Foreman has pointed out that ontological maximalism can actually be used to argue in favor of CH, because among models that have the same reals, models with "more" sets of reals have a better chance of satisfying CH.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Another viewpoint is that the conception of set is not specific enough to determine whether CH is true or false.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] This viewpoint was advanced as early as 1923 by Skolem, even before Gödel's first incompleteness theorem.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Skolem argued on the basis of what is now known as Skolem's paradox, and it was later supported by the independence of CH from the axioms of ZFC since these axioms are enough to establish the elementary properties of sets and cardinalities.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In order to argue against this viewpoint, it would be sufficient to demonstrate new axioms that are supported by intuition and resolve CH in one direction or another.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Although the axiom of constructibility does resolve CH, it is not generally considered to be intuitively true any more than CH is generally considered to be false.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] At least two other axioms have been proposed that have implications for the continuum hypothesis, although these axioms have not currently found wide acceptance in the mathematical community.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In 1986, Chris Freiling presented an argument against CH by showing that the negation of CH is equivalent to Freiling's axiom of symmetry, a statement derived by arguing from particular intuitions about probabilities.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Freiling believes this axiom is "intuitively clear" but others have disagreed.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] A difficult argument against CH developed by W.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Hugh Woodin has attracted considerable attention since the year 2000.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Foreman does not reject Woodin's argument outright but urges caution.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Woodin proposed a new hypothesis that he labeled the "(*)-axiom", or "Star axiom".
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The Star axiom would imply that $2^{\aleph _{0}}$ is $\aleph _{2}$ , thus falsifying CH.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The Star axiom was bolstered by an independent May 2021 proof showing the Star axiom can be derived from a variation of Martin's maximum.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] However, Woodin stated in the 2010s that he now instead believes CH to be true, based on his belief in his new "ultimate L" conjecture.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Solomon Feferman argued that CH is not a definite mathematical problem.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] He conjectured that CH is not definite according to this notion, and proposed that CH should, therefore, be considered not to have a truth value.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Peter Koellner wrote a critical commentary on Feferman's article.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Joel David Hamkins proposes a multiverse approach to set theory and argues that "the continuum hypothesis is settled on the multiverse view by our extensive knowledge about how it behaves in the multiverse, and, as a result, it can no longer be settled in the manner formerly hoped for".
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In a related vein, Saharon Shelah wrote that he does "not agree with the pure Platonic view that the interesting problems in set theory can be decided, that we just have to discover the additional axiom.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] My mental picture is that we have many possible set theories, all conforming to ZFC".
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The *generalized continuum hypothesis* (GCH) states that if an infinite set's cardinality lies between that of an infinite set S and that of the power set ${\mathcal {P}}(S)$ of S, then it has the same cardinality as either S or ${\mathcal {P}}(S)$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] That is, for any infinite cardinal $\lambda$ there is no cardinal $\kappa$ such that $\lambda <\kappa <2^{\lambda }$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] (occasionally called *Cantor's aleph hypothesis*).
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The beth numbers provide an alternative notation for this condition: $\aleph _{\alpha }=\beth _{\alpha }$ for every ordinal $\alpha$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The continuum hypothesis is the special case for the ordinal $\alpha =1$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] GCH was first suggested by Philip Jourdain.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] For the early history of GCH, see Moore.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Like CH, GCH is also independent of ZFC, but Sierpiński proved that ZF + GCH implies the axiom of choice (AC) (and therefore the negation of the axiom of determinacy, AD), so choice and GCH are not independent in ZF; there are no models of ZF in which GCH holds and AC fails.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] To prove this, Sierpiński showed GCH implies that every cardinality n is smaller than some aleph number, and thus can be ordered.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] This is done by showing that n is smaller than $2^{\aleph _{0}+n}$ which is smaller than its own Hartogs number—this uses the equality $2^{\aleph _{0}+n}\,=\,2\cdot \,2^{\aleph _{0}+n}$ ; for the full proof, see Gillman.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Kurt Gödel showed that GCH is a consequence of ZF + V=L (the axiom that every set is constructible relative to the ordinals), and is therefore consistent with ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] As GCH implies CH, Cohen's model in which CH fails is a model in which GCH fails, and thus GCH is not provable from ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Easton used the method of forcing developed by Cohen to prove Easton's theorem, which shows it is consistent with ZFC for arbitrarily large cardinals $\aleph _{\alpha }$ to fail to satisfy $2^{\aleph _{\alpha }}=\aleph _{\alpha +1}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Much later, Foreman and Woodin proved that (assuming the consistency of very large cardinals) it is consistent that $2^{\kappa }>\kappa ^{+}$ holds for every infinite cardinal $\kappa$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Later Woodin extended this by showing the consistency of $2^{\kappa }=\kappa ^{++}$ for every $\kappa$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Carmi Merimovich showed that, for each *n* ≥ 1, it is consistent with ZFC that for each infinite cardinal κ, 2*κ* is the nth successor of κ (assuming the consistency of some large cardinal axioms).
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] On the other hand, László Patai proved that if γ is an ordinal and for each infinite cardinal κ, 2*κ* is the γth successor of κ, then γ is finite.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] For any infinite sets A and B, if there is an injection from A to B then there is an injection from subsets of A to subsets of B.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Thus for any infinite cardinals A and B, $A<B\to 2^{A}\leq 2^{B}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] If A and B are finite, the stronger inequality $A<B\to 2^{A}<2^{B}$ holds.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] GCH implies that this strict, stronger inequality holds for infinite cardinals as well as finite cardinals.
[src:forcing-set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Although the generalized continuum hypothesis refers directly only to cardinal exponentiation with 2 as the base, one can deduce from it the values of cardinal exponentiation $\aleph _{\alpha }^{\aleph _{\beta }}$ in all cases.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In set theory, **forcing** is a technique for proving consistency and independence results.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Intuitively, forcing can be thought of as a technique to expand the set theoretical universe V to a larger universe $V[G]$ by introducing a new "generic" object G .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Forcing was first used by Paul Cohen in 1963, to prove the independence of the axiom of choice and the continuum hypothesis from Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] It has been considerably reworked and simplified in the following years, and has since served as a powerful technique, both in set theory and in areas of mathematical logic such as computability theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Descriptive set theory uses the notions of forcing from both computability theory and set theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Forcing has also been used in model theory, but it is common in model theory to define genericity directly without mention of forcing.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Forcing is usually used to construct an expanded universe that satisfies some desired property.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For example, the expanded universe might contain many new real numbers (at least $\aleph _{2}$ of them), identified with subsets of the set $\mathbb {N}$ of natural numbers, that were not there in the old universe, and thereby violate the continuum hypothesis.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In order to intuitively justify such an expansion, it is best to think of the "old universe" as a model M of the set theory, which is itself a set in the "real universe" V .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] By the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem, M can be chosen to be a "bare bones" model that is externally countable, which guarantees that there will be many subsets (in V ) of $\mathbb {N}$ that are not in M .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Specifically, there is an ordinal $\aleph _{2}^{M}$ that "plays the role of the cardinal $\aleph _{2}$ " in M , but is actually countable in V .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Working in V , it should be easy to find one distinct subset of $\mathbb {N}$ per each element of $\aleph _{2}^{M}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] However, in some sense, it may be desirable to "construct the expanded model $M[X]$ within M ".
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] This would help ensure that $M[X]$ "resembles" M in certain aspects, such as $\aleph _{2}^{M[X]}$ being the same as $\aleph _{2}^{M}$ (more generally, that *cardinal collapse* does not occur), and allow fine control over the properties of $M[X]$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] More precisely, every member of $M[X]$ should be given a (non-unique) *name* in M .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The name can be thought as an expression in terms of X , just like in a simple field extension $L=K(\theta )$ every element of L can be expressed in terms of $\theta$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] A major component of forcing is manipulating those names within M , so sometimes it may help to directly think of M as "the universe", knowing that the theory of forcing guarantees that $M[X]$ will correspond to an actual model.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] A subtle point of forcing is that, if X is taken to be an *arbitrary* "missing subset" of some set in M , then the $M[X]$ constructed "within M " may not even be a model.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] This is because X may encode "special" information about M that is invisible within M (e.g. the countability of M ), and thus prove the existence of sets that are "too complex for M to describe".
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Forcing avoids such problems by requiring the newly introduced set X to be a **generic set** relative to M .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Some statements are "forced" to hold for any generic X : For example, a generic X is "forced" to be infinite.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Furthermore, any property (describable in M ) of a generic set is "forced" to hold under some **forcing condition**.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The concept of "forcing" can be defined within M , and it gives M enough reasoning power to prove that $M[X]$ is indeed a model that satisfies the desired properties.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Cohen's original technique, now called ramified forcing, is slightly different from the **unramified forcing** expounded here.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Forcing is also equivalent to the method of Boolean-valued models, which some feel is conceptually more natural and intuitive, but usually much more difficult to apply.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In order for the above approach to work smoothly, M must in fact be a standard transitive model in V , so that membership and other elementary notions can be handled intuitively in both M and V .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] A standard transitive model can be obtained from any standard model through the Mostowski collapse lemma, but the existence of any standard model of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ (or any variant thereof) is in itself a stronger assumption than the consistency of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] As the goal of a forcing argument is to prove consistency results, this is enough since any inconsistency in a theory must manifest with a derivation of a finite length, and thus involve only a finite number of axioms.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Each forcing condition can be regarded as a *finite* piece of information regarding the object X adjoined to the model.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] There are many different ways of providing information about an object, which give rise to different **forcing notions**.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] A general approach to formalizing forcing notions is to regard forcing conditions as abstract objects with a poset structure.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] A **forcing poset** is an ordered triple, $(\mathbb {P} ,\leq ,\mathbf {1} )$ , where $\leq$ is a preorder on $\mathbb {P}$ , and $\mathbf {1}$ is the largest element.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Members of $\mathbb {P}$ are the **forcing conditions** (or just **conditions**).
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The order relation $p\leq q$ means " p is **stronger** than q ".
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In other words, it must be possible to strengthen any forcing condition p in at least two incompatible directions.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Intuitively, this is because p is only a finite piece of information, whereas an infinite piece of information is needed to determine X .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Some authors require $\leq$ to also be antisymmetric, so that the relation is a partial order.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Some use the term partial order anyway, conflicting with standard terminology, while some use the term preorder.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The largest element can be dispensed with.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The reverse ordering is also used, most notably by Saharon Shelah and his co-authors.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Let S be any infinite set (such as $\mathbb {N}$ ), and let the generic object in question be a new subset $X\subseteq S$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In Cohen's original formulation of forcing, each forcing condition is a *finite* set of sentences, either of the form $a\in X$ or $a\notin X$ , that are self-consistent (i.e. $a\in X$ *and* $a\notin X$ for the same value of a do not appear in the same condition).
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] This forcing notion is usually called **Cohen forcing**.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The forcing poset for Cohen forcing can be formally written as $(\operatorname {Fin} (S,2),\supseteq ,\emptyset )$ , the finite partial functions from S to $2~{\stackrel {\text{df}}{=}}~\{0,1\}$ under *reverse* inclusion.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Cohen forcing satisfies the splitting condition because given any condition p , one can always find an element $a\in S$ not mentioned in p , and add either the sentence $a\in X$ or $a\notin X$ to p to get two new forcing conditions, incompatible with each other.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Another instructive example of a forcing poset is $(\operatorname {Bor} (I),\subseteq ,I)$ , where $I=[0,1]$ and $\operatorname {Bor} (I)$ is the collection of Borel subsets of I having non-zero Lebesgue measure.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The generic object associated with this forcing poset is a **random real number** $r\in [0,1]$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] It can be shown that r falls in every Borel subset of $[0,1]$ with measure 1, provided that the Borel subset is "described" in the original unexpanded universe (this can be formalized with the concept of *Borel codes*).
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Each forcing condition can be regarded as a random event with probability equal to its measure.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Due to the ready intuition this example can provide, probabilistic language is sometimes used with other divergent forcing posets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Even though each individual forcing condition p cannot fully determine the generic object X , the set $G\subseteq \mathbb {P}$ of all true forcing conditions does determine X .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In fact, without loss of generality, G is commonly considered to *be* the generic object adjoined to M , so the expanded model is called $M[G]$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] It is usually easy enough to show that the originally desired object X is indeed in the model $M[G]$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Under this convention, the concept of "generic object" can be described in a general way.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Specifically, the set G should be a **generic filter** on $\mathbb {P}$ relative to M .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Given that M is a countable model, the existence of a generic filter G follows from the Rasiowa–Sikorski lemma.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In fact, slightly more is true: Given a condition $p\in \mathbb {P}$ , one can find a generic filter G such that $p\in G$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Due to the splitting condition on $\mathbb {P}$ , if G is a filter, then $\mathbb {P} \setminus G$ is dense.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] If $G\in M$ , then $\mathbb {P} \setminus G\in M$ because M is a model of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For this reason, a generic filter is never in M .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Associated with a forcing poset $\mathbb {P}$ is the class $V^{(\mathbb {P} )}$ of $\mathbb {P}$ -**names**.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The $\mathbb {P}$ -names are, in fact, an expansion of the universe.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Since $\mathbf {1} \in G$ , it follows that $\operatorname {val} ({\check {x}},G)=x$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In a sense, ${\check {x}}$ is a "name for x " that does not depend on the specific choice of G .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The concepts of $\mathbb {P}$ -names, interpretations, and ${\check {x}}$ may be defined by transfinite recursion.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The interpretation map and the map $x\mapsto {\check {x}}$ can similarly be defined with a hierarchical construction.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Given a generic filter $G\subseteq \mathbb {P}$ , one proceeds as follows.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The subclass of $\mathbb {P}$ -names in M is denoted $M^{(\mathbb {P} )}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] To reduce the study of the set theory of $M[G]$ to that of M , one works with the "forcing language", which is built up like ordinary first-order logic, with membership as the binary relation and all the $\mathbb {P}$ -names as constants.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The special case $\mathbf {1} \Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }\varphi$ is often written as " $\mathbb {P} \Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }\varphi$ " or simply " $\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }\varphi$ ".
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Such statements are true in $M[G]$ , no matter what G is.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] This has the effect that all the properties of $M[G]$ are really properties of M , and the verification of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ in $M[G]$ becomes straightforward.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] There are many different but equivalent ways to define the forcing relation $\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }$ in M .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] One way to simplify the definition is to first define a modified forcing relation $\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }^{*}$ that is strictly stronger than $\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The modified relation $\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }^{*}$ still satisfies the three key properties of forcing, but $p\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }^{*}\varphi$ and $p\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }^{*}\varphi '$ are not necessarily equivalent even if the first-order formulae $\varphi$ and $\varphi '$ are equivalent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The unmodified forcing relation can then be defined as $p\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }\varphi \iff p\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }^{*}\neg \neg \varphi .$ In fact, Cohen's original concept of forcing is essentially $\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }^{*}$ rather than $\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Other symbols of the forcing language can be defined in terms of these symbols: For example, $u=v$ means $\neg (u\neq v)$ , $\forall x\,\varphi (x)$ means $\neg \exists x\,\neg \varphi (x)$ , etc.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Cases 1 and 2 depend on each other and on case 3, but the recursion always refers to $\mathbb {P}$ -names with lesser ranks, so transfinite induction allows the definition to go through.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] By construction, $\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }^{*}$ (and thus $\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }$ ) automatically satisfies **Definability**.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The proof that $\Vdash _{M,\mathbb {P} }^{*}$ also satisfies **Truth** and **Coherence** is by inductively inspecting each of the five cases above.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Cases 4 and 5 are trivial (thanks to the choice of $\vee$ and $\exists$ as the elementary symbols), cases 1 and 2 rely only on the assumption that G is a filter, and only case 3 requires G to be a *generic* filter.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Formally, an internal definition of the forcing relation (such as the one presented above) is actually a transformation of an arbitrary formula $\varphi (x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})$ to another formula $p\Vdash _{\mathbb {P} }\varphi (u_{1},\dots ,u_{n})$ where p and $\mathbb {P}$ are additional variables.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] This is the sense in which the forcing relation is indeed "definable in M ".
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The discussion above can be summarized by the fundamental consistency result that, given a forcing poset $\mathbb {P}$ , we may assume the existence of a generic filter G , not belonging to the universe V , such that $V[G]$ is again a set-theoretic universe that models ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Furthermore, all truths in $V[G]$ may be reduced to truths in V involving the forcing relation.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Both styles, adjoining G to either a countable transitive model M or the whole universe V , are commonly used.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Less commonly seen is the approach using the "internal" definition of forcing, in which no mention of set or class models is made.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] This was Cohen's original method, and in one elaboration, it becomes the method of Boolean-valued analysis.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The simplest nontrivial forcing poset is $(\operatorname {Fin} (\omega ,2),\supseteq ,\emptyset )$ , the finite partial functions from $\omega$ to $2~{\stackrel {\text{df}}{=}}~\{0,1\}$ under *reverse* inclusion.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] That is, a condition p is essentially two disjoint finite subsets ${p^{-1}}[1]$ and ${p^{-1}}[0]$ of $\omega$ , to be thought of as the "yes" and "no" parts of p , with no information provided on values outside the domain of p .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] " q is stronger than p " means that $q\supseteq p$ , in other words, the "yes" and "no" parts of q are supersets of the "yes" and "no" parts of p , and in that sense, provide more information.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Let G be a generic filter for this poset.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] If p and q are both in G , then $p\cup q$ is a condition because G is a filter.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] This means that $g=\bigcup G$ is a well-defined partial function from $\omega$ to 2 because any two conditions in G agree on their common domain.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] (Given any p , if n is not in p 's domain, adjoin a value for n —the result is in $D_{n}$ .) A condition $p\in G\cap D_{n}$ has n in its domain, and since $p\subseteq g$ , we find that $g(n)$ is defined.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Let $X={g^{-1}}[1]$ , the set of all "yes" members of the generic conditions.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] It is possible to give a name for X directly.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Then $\operatorname {val} ({\underline {X}},G)=X.$ Now suppose that $A\subseteq \omega$ in V .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] (Given any p , find n that is not in its domain, and adjoin a value for n contrary to the status of " $n\in A$ ".) Then any $p\in G\cap D_{A}$ witnesses $X\neq A$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] To summarize, X is a "new" subset of $\omega$ , necessarily infinite.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Replacing $\omega$ with $\omega \times \omega _{2}$ , that is, considering instead finite partial functions whose inputs are of the form $(n,\alpha )$ , with $n<\omega$ and $\alpha <\omega _{2}$ , and whose outputs are 0 or 1 , one gets $\omega _{2}$ new subsets of $\omega$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] then each $D_{\alpha ,\beta }$ is dense, and a generic condition in it proves that the *α*th new set disagrees somewhere with the $\beta$ th new set.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] This is not yet the falsification of the continuum hypothesis.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] One must prove that no new maps have been introduced that map $\omega$ onto $\omega _{1}$ , or $\omega _{1}$ onto $\omega _{2}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For example, if one considers instead $\operatorname {Fin} (\omega ,\omega _{1})$ , finite partial functions from $\omega$ to $\omega _{1}$ , the first uncountable ordinal, one gets in $V[G]$ a bijection from $\omega$ to $\omega _{1}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In other words, $\omega _{1}$ has *collapsed*, and in the forcing extension, is a countable ordinal.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The last step in showing the independence of the continuum hypothesis, then, is to show that Cohen forcing does not collapse cardinals.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For this, a sufficient combinatorial property is that all of the antichains of the forcing poset are countable.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] A (strong) antichain A of $\mathbb {P}$ is a subset such that if $p,q\in A$ and $p\neq q$ , then p and q are **incompatible** (written $p\perp q$ ), meaning there is no r in $\mathbb {P}$ such that $r\leq p$ and $r\leq q$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In the example on Borel sets, incompatibility means that $p\cap q$ has zero measure.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In the example on finite partial functions, incompatibility means that $p\cup q$ is not a function, in other words, p and q assign different values to some domain input.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] $\mathbb {P}$ is said to satisfy the *countable chain condition* (c.c.c.) if every antichain in $\mathbb {P}$ is countable.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] (The name, which is obviously inappropriate, is a holdover from older terminology.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] It is easy to see that $\operatorname {Bor} (I)$ satisfies the c.c.c. because the measures add up to at most 1 .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Also, $\operatorname {Fin} (E,2)$ satisfies the c.c.c., but the proof is more difficult.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Now, pick an arbitrary $p\in W_{k}$ , and pick from $W_{k}$ any q that is not one of the countably many members that have a domain member in common with p .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In other words, $\operatorname {Fin} (E,2)$ -antichains are countable.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The importance of antichains in forcing is that for most purposes, dense sets and maximal antichains are equivalent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] A *maximal* antichain A is one that cannot be extended to a larger antichain.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] This means that every element $p\in \mathbb {P}$ is compatible with some member of A .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The existence of a maximal antichain follows from Zorn's Lemma.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Then D is dense, and $G\cap D\neq \varnothing$ if and only if $G\cap A\neq \varnothing$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Conversely, given a dense set D , Zorn's Lemma shows that there exists a maximal antichain $A\subseteq D$ , and then $G\cap D\neq \varnothing$ if and only if $G\cap A\neq \varnothing$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Assume that $\mathbb {P}$ satisfies the c.c.c.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Given $x,y\in V$ , with $f:x\to y$ a function in $V[G]$ , one can approximate f inside V as follows.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Let u be a name for f (by the definition of $V[G]$ ) and let p be a condition that forces u to be a function from x to y .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] By the definability of forcing, this definition makes sense within V .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] By the coherence of forcing, a different b must come from an incompatible p .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In summary, f is unknown in V as it depends on G , but it is not wildly unknown for a c.c.c.-forcing.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] One can identify a countable set of guesses for what the value of f is at any input, independent of G .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] This has the following very important consequence.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] If in $V[G]$ , $f:\alpha \to \beta$ is a surjection from one infinite ordinal onto another, then there is a surjection $g:\omega \times \alpha \to \beta$ in V , and consequently, a surjection $h:\alpha \to \beta$ in V .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In particular, cardinals cannot collapse.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The exact value of the continuum in the above Cohen model, and variants like $\operatorname {Fin} (\omega \times \kappa ,2)$ for cardinals $\kappa$ in general, was worked out by Robert M.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Solovay, who also worked out how to violate ${\mathsf {GCH}}$ (the generalized continuum hypothesis), for regular cardinals only, a finite number of times.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For example, in the above Cohen model, if ${\mathsf {CH}}$ holds in V , then $2^{\aleph _{0}}=\aleph _{2}$ holds in $V[G]$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Easton worked out the proper class version of violating the ${\mathsf {GCH}}$ for regular cardinals, basically showing that the known restrictions, (monotonicity, Cantor's theorem and König's theorem), were the only ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ -provable restrictions (see Easton's theorem).
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Easton's work was notable in that it involved forcing with a proper class of conditions.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In general, the method of forcing with a proper class of conditions fails to give a model of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For example, forcing with $\operatorname {Fin} (\omega \times \mathbf {On} ,2)$ , where $\mathbf {On}$ is the proper class of all ordinals, makes the continuum a proper class.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] On the other hand, forcing with $\operatorname {Fin} (\omega ,\mathbf {On} )$ introduces a countable enumeration of the ordinals.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In both cases, the resulting $V[G]$ is visibly not a model of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] At one time, it was thought that more sophisticated forcing would also allow an arbitrary variation in the powers of singular cardinals.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] However, this has turned out to be a difficult, subtle and even surprising problem, with several more restrictions provable in ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ and with the forcing models depending on the consistency of various large-cardinal properties.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Random forcing can be defined as forcing over the set P of all compact subsets of $[0,1]$ of positive measure, ordered by the relation $\subseteq$ (a smaller set in the context of inclusion is a smaller set in the ordering, and represents a condition with more information).
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For any Borel subset $B\subseteq [0,1]$ of measure 1, the set $D_{B}=\{p\in P:p\subseteq B\}$ is dense.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For any filter G and any pair of elements $p_{1},p_{2}\in G$ there is $q\in G$ such that $q\leq p_{1},p_{2}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In this ordering, this means that any filter is closed under finite intersection.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Therefore, by Cantor's intersection theorem, the intersection of *all* the elements in any filter is nonempty.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] If G is a filter intersecting the dense set $D_{n}$ for any positive integer n , then the filter G contains conditions of arbitrarily small positive diameter.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Therefore, the intersection of all conditions from G has diameter 0.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] But the only nonempty sets of diameter 0 are singletons.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] So there is exactly one real number $r_{G}$ such that $r_{G}\in \bigcap G$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Let $B\subseteq [0,1]$ be any Borel set of measure 1.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] However, a generic filter over a countable transitive model M is not in M .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The real $r_{G}$ defined by G is provably not an element of M .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] One issue with this construction is that if $p\in P$ , then $M\models$ " p is compact", but from the viewpoint of some larger universe $V\supseteq M$ , p can be non-compact and the intersection of all conditions from the generic filter G can then be empty.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] To fix this, we consider the set $C=\{{\bar {p}}:p\in G\}$ of topological closures of conditions from G .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Because ${\bar {p}}\supseteq p$ , and because G is closed under finite intersection, Cantor's intersection theorem applies and the intersection of the set C is nonempty.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Since $\operatorname {diam} ({\bar {p}})=\operatorname {diam} (p)$ and the ground model M inherits a metric from the universe V , the set C has elements of arbitrarily small diameter.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Finally, there is exactly one real that belongs to all members of the set C .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The generic filter G can be reconstructed from $r_{G}$ as $G=\{p\in P:r_{G}\in {\bar {p}}\}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Every Borel set can be (non-uniquely) built up, starting from intervals with rational endpoints and applying the operations of complement and countable union, a countable number of times.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The record of such a construction is called a *Borel code*.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Given a Borel set B in V , one recovers a Borel code, and then applies the same construction sequence in $M[G]$ , getting a Borel set $B^{*}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] It can be proven that one gets the same set independent of the code chosen for B , and that basic properties are preserved.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For example, if $B\subseteq C$ , then $B^{*}\subseteq C^{*}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] If B has measure zero, then $B^{*}$ has measure zero.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] This mapping $B\mapsto B^{*}$ is injective.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For any set $B\subseteq [0,1]$ such that $B\in M$ and $M\models$ " B is a Borel set of measure 1" one has $r_{G}\in B^{*}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] This means that $r_{G}$ is an "infinite random sequence of 0s and 1s" from the viewpoint of M , which means that it satisfies all statistical tests from the ground model M .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Because of this mutual inter-definability between r and G , one generally writes $M[r]$ for $M[G]$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] A different interpretation of reals in $M[G]$ was provided by Dana Scott.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Rational numbers in $M[G]$ have names that correspond to countably-many distinct rational values assigned to a maximal antichain of Borel sets – in other words, a certain rational-valued function on $I=[0,1]$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Real numbers in $M[G]$ then correspond to Dedekind cuts of such functions, that is, measurable functions.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Perhaps more clearly, the method can be explained in terms of Boolean-valued models.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In these, any statement is assigned a truth value from some complete atomless Boolean algebra, rather than just a true/false value.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Then an ultrafilter is picked in this Boolean algebra, which assigns values true/false to statements of our theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The point is that the resulting theory has a model that contains this ultrafilter, which can be understood as a new model obtained by extending the old one with this ultrafilter.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] By picking a Boolean-valued model in an appropriate way, we can get a model that has the desired property.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In it, only statements that must be true (are "forced" to be true) will be true, in a sense (since it has this extension/minimality property).
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In forcing, we usually seek to show that some sentence is consistent with ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ (or optionally some extension of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ ).
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] One way to interpret the argument is to assume that ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ is consistent and then prove that ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ combined with the new sentence is also consistent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Each "condition" is a finite piece of information—the idea is that only finite pieces are relevant for consistency, since, by the compactness theorem, a theory is satisfiable if and only if every finite subset of its axioms is satisfiable.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Then we can pick an infinite set of consistent conditions to extend our model.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Therefore, assuming the consistency of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ , we prove the consistency of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ extended by this infinite set.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] By Gödel's second incompleteness theorem, one cannot prove the consistency of any sufficiently strong formal theory, such as ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ , using only the axioms of the theory itself, unless the theory is inconsistent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Consequently, mathematicians do not attempt to prove the consistency of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ using only the axioms of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ , or to prove that ${\mathsf {ZFC}}+H$ is consistent for any hypothesis H using only ${\mathsf {ZFC}}+H$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For this reason, the aim of a consistency proof is to prove the consistency of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}+H$ relative to the consistency of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The general schema of relative consistency proofs follows.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For any given proof, ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ can verify the validity of this proof.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] This is provable by induction on the length of the proof.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] The core of the relative consistency proof is proving (**).
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] A ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ proof of $\operatorname {Con} (T+H)$ can be constructed for any given finite subset T of the ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ axioms (by ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ instruments of course).
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ , it is provable that for any condition p , the set of formulas (evaluated by names) forced by p is deductively closed.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Furthermore, for any ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ axiom, ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ proves that this axiom is forced by $\mathbf {1}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Then it suffices to prove that there is at least one condition that forces H .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] In the case of Boolean-valued forcing, the procedure is similar: proving that the Boolean value of H is not $\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Another approach uses the reflection principle.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For any given finite set of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ axioms, there is a ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ proof that this set of axioms has a countable transitive model.
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] For any given finite set T of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ axioms, there is a finite set $T'$ of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ axioms such that ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ proves that if a countable transitive model M satisfies $T'$ , then $M[G]$ satisfies T .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Suppose it can also be shown that there is finite set $T''$ of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ axioms such that if a countable transitive model M satisfies $T''$ , then $M[G]$ satisfies the hypothesis H .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Then for any given finite set T of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ axioms, ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ proves $\operatorname {Con} (T+H)$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Sometimes in (**), a stronger theory S than ${\mathsf {ZFC}}$ is used for proving $\operatorname {Con} (T+H)$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Then we have proof of the consistency of ${\mathsf {ZFC}}+H$ relative to the consistency of S .
[src:forcing-set-theory/forcing-mathematics] Note that ${\mathsf {ZFC}}\vdash \operatorname {Con} ({\mathsf {ZFC}})\leftrightarrow \operatorname {Con} ({\mathsf {ZFL}})$ , where ${\mathsf {ZFL}}$ is ${\mathsf {ZF}}+(V=L)$ (the axiom of constructibility).
[src:forcing-set-theory/generic-filter] In the mathematical field of set theory, a **generic filter** is a kind of object used in the theory of forcing, a technique used for many purposes, but especially to establish the independence of certain propositions from certain formal theories, such as ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/generic-filter] For example, Paul Cohen used forcing to establish that ZFC, if consistent, cannot prove the continuum hypothesis, which states that there are exactly $\aleph _{1}$ real numbers.
[src:forcing-set-theory/generic-filter] In the contemporary re-interpretation of Cohen's proof, it proceeds by constructing a generic filter that codes more than $\aleph _{1}$ reals, without changing the value of $\aleph _{1}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/generic-filter] Similarly, if *M* is a transitive model of ZFC (or some sufficient fragment of ZFC), with *P* an element of *M* (partially ordered by ∈), then *F* is said to be ***M*-generic**, or sometimes **generic over *M***, if *F* meets all dense open subsets of *P* that are elements of *M*.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] In the mathematical field of set theory, a **large cardinal property** is a certain kind of property of transfinite cardinal numbers.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] Cardinals with such properties are, as the name suggests, generally very "large" (for example, bigger than the least α such that *α* = *ω**α*).
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] The proposition that such cardinals exist cannot be proved in the most common axiomatization of set theory, namely ZFC, and such propositions can be viewed as ways of measuring how "much", beyond ZFC, one needs to assume to be able to prove certain desired results.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] In other words, they can be seen, in Dana Scott's phrase, as quantifying the fact "that if you want more you have to assume more".
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] There is a rough convention that results provable from ZFC alone may be stated without hypotheses, but that if the proof requires other assumptions (such as the existence of large cardinals), these should be stated.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] Whether this is simply a linguistic convention, or something more, is a controversial point among distinct philosophical schools (see Motivations and epistemic status below).
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] A **large cardinal axiom** is an axiom stating that there exists a cardinal (or perhaps many of them) with some specified large cardinal property.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] Most working set theorists believe that the large cardinal axioms that are currently being considered are consistent with ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] These axioms are strong enough to imply the consistency of ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] This has the consequence (via Gödel's second incompleteness theorem) that their consistency with ZFC cannot be proven in ZFC (assuming ZFC is consistent).
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] There is no generally agreed-upon precise definition of what a large cardinal property is, though essentially everyone agrees that those in the list of large cardinal properties are large cardinal properties.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] A necessary condition for a property of cardinal numbers to be a *large cardinal property* is that the existence of such a cardinal is not known to be inconsistent with ZF and that such a cardinal *Κ* would be an uncountable initial ordinal for which *L**Κ* is a model of ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] If ZFC is consistent, then ZFC does *not* imply that any such large cardinals exist.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] A remarkable observation about large cardinal axioms is that they appear to occur in strict linear order by consistency strength.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] ZFC + *A*2 proves that ZFC + *A*1 is consistent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] These are mutually exclusive, unless one of the theories in question is actually inconsistent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] In case 1, we say that *A*1 and *A*2 are equiconsistent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] In case 2, we say that *A*1 is consistency-wise stronger than *A*2 (vice versa for case 3).
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] If *A*2 is stronger than *A*1, then ZFC + *A*1 cannot prove ZFC + *A*2 is consistent, even with the additional hypothesis that ZFC + *A*1 is itself consistent (provided of course that it really is).
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] This follows from Gödel's second incompleteness theorem.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] The observation that large cardinal axioms are linearly ordered by consistency strength is just that: an observation, not a theorem.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] (Without an accepted definition of large cardinal property, it is not subject to proof in the ordinary sense.) It is also not known in every instance which of the three logical relationships holds.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] Saharon Shelah has asked, "[i]s there some theorem explaining this, or is our vision just more uniform than we realize?" Woodin, however, deduces this from the Ω-conjecture, the main unsolved problem of his Ω-logic.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] It is also noteworthy that many combinatorial statements are exactly equiconsistent with some large cardinal rather than, say, being intermediate between them.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] The ordering of large cardinal axioms by consistency strength is not necessarily the same as their ordering by the size of their smallest witnesses.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] For example, the existence of a huge cardinal is much stronger, in terms of consistency strength, than the existence of a supercompact cardinal, but, assuming both exist, the first huge cardinal is smaller than the first supercompact one.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] Large cardinals are understood in the context of the von Neumann universe V, which is built up by transfinitely iterating the powerset operation, which collects together all subsets of a given set.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] Typically, models in which large cardinal axioms *fail* can be seen in some natural way as submodels of those in which the axioms hold.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] For example, if there is an inaccessible cardinal, then "cutting the universe off" at the height of the first such cardinal yields a universe in which there is no inaccessible cardinal.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] Or if there is a measurable cardinal, then iterating the *definable* powerset operation rather than the full one yields Gödel's constructible universe, L, which does not satisfy the statement "there is a measurable cardinal" (even though it contains the measurable cardinal as an ordinal).
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] Moreover the consequences of large cardinal axioms seem to fall into natural patterns (see Maddy, "Believing the Axioms, II").
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] For these reasons, such set theorists tend to consider large cardinal axioms to have a preferred status among extensions of ZFC, one not shared by axioms of less clear motivation (such as Martin's axiom) or others that they consider intuitively unlikely (such as V = L).
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] The hardcore realists in this group would state, more simply, that large cardinal axioms are *true*.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] This point of view is by no means universal among set theorists.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] Some formalists would assert that standard set theory is by definition the study of the consequences of ZFC, and while they might not be opposed in principle to studying the consequences of other systems, they see no reason to single out large cardinals as preferred.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] There are also realists who deny that ontological maximalism is a proper motivation, and even believe that large cardinal axioms are false.
[src:forcing-set-theory/large-cardinal] And finally, there are some who deny that the negations of large cardinal axioms *are* restrictive, pointing out that (for example) there can be a transitive set model in L that believes there exists a measurable cardinal, even though L itself does not satisfy that proposition.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] In set theory, **Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory**, named after mathematicians Ernst Zermelo and Abraham Fraenkel, is an axiomatic system that was proposed in the early twentieth century in order to formulate a theory of sets free of paradoxes such as Russell's paradox.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Today, Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory, with the historically controversial axiom of choice (AC) included, is the standard form of axiomatic set theory and as such is the most common foundation of mathematics.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory with the axiom of choice included is abbreviated **ZFC**, where C stands for "choice", and **ZF** refers to the axioms of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory with the axiom of choice excluded.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Informally, Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory is intended to formalize a single primitive notion, that of a hereditary well-founded set, so that all entities in the universe of discourse are such sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Thus the axioms of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory refer only to pure sets and prevent its models from containing urelements (elements that are not themselves sets).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Furthermore, proper classes (collections of mathematical objects defined by a property shared by their members where the collections are too big to be sets) can only be treated indirectly.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Specifically, Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory does not allow for the existence of a universal set (a set containing all sets) nor for unrestricted comprehension, thereby avoiding Russell's paradox.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Von Neumann–Bernays–Gödel set theory (NBG) is a commonly used conservative extension of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory that does allow explicit treatment of proper classes.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] There are many equivalent formulations of the axioms of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Most of the axioms state the existence of particular sets defined from other sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] For example, the axiom of pairing implies that given any two sets a and b there is a new set $\{a,b\}$ containing exactly a and b .
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Other axioms describe properties of set membership.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] A goal of the axioms is that each axiom should be true if interpreted as a statement about the collection of all sets in the von Neumann universe (also known as the cumulative hierarchy).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The metamathematics of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory has been extensively studied.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Landmark results in this area established the logical independence of the axiom of choice from the remaining Zermelo-Fraenkel axioms and of the continuum hypothesis from ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The consistency of a theory such as ZFC cannot be proved within the theory itself, as shown by Gödel's second incompleteness theorem.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The modern study of set theory was initiated by Georg Cantor and Richard Dedekind in the 1870s.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] However, the discovery of paradoxes in naive set theory, such as Russell's paradox, led to the desire for a more rigorous form of set theory that was free of these paradoxes.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] In 1908, Ernst Zermelo proposed the first axiomatic set theory, Zermelo set theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Moreover, one of Zermelo's axioms invoked a concept, that of a "definite" property, whose operational meaning was not clear.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] In 1922, Fraenkel and Thoralf Skolem independently proposed operationalizing a "definite" property as one that could be formulated as a well-formed formula in a first-order logic whose atomic formulas were limited to set membership and identity.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] They also independently proposed replacing the axiom schema of specification with the axiom schema of replacement.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Appending this schema, as well as the axiom of regularity (first proposed by John von Neumann), to Zermelo set theory yields the theory ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Formally, ZFC is a one-sorted theory in first-order logic.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The equality symbol can be treated as either a primitive logical symbol or a high-level abbreviation for having exactly the same elements.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The signature has a single predicate symbol, usually denoted $\in$ , which is a predicate symbol of arity 2 (a binary relation symbol).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] This symbol symbolizes a set membership relation.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] For example, the formula $a\in b$ means that *a is an element of the set b* (also read as *a is a member of b*).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] There are different ways to formulate the formal language.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Some authors may choose a different set of connectives or quantifiers.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] For example, the logical connective NAND alone can encode the other connectives, a property known as functional completeness.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] This section attempts to strike a balance between simplicity and intuitiveness.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] A well-formed formula can be thought as a syntax tree.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The leaf nodes are always atomic formulae.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Nodes $\land$ and $\lor$ have exactly two child nodes, while nodes $\lnot$ , $\forall x$ and $\exists x$ have exactly one.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] There are countably infinitely many wffs; however, each wff has a finite number of nodes.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] There are many equivalent formulations of the ZFC axioms.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The following particular axiom set is from Kunen (1980).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The axioms in order below are expressed in a mixture of first-order logic and high-level abbreviations.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Axioms 1–8 form ZF, while the axiom 9 turns ZF into ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Following Kunen (1980), we use the equivalent well-ordering theorem in place of the axiom of choice for axiom 9.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] All formulations of ZFC imply that at least one set exists.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Kunen includes an axiom that directly asserts the existence of a set, although he notes that he does so only "for emphasis".
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Its omission here can be justified in two ways.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] First, in the standard semantics of first-order logic in which ZFC is typically formalized, the domain of discourse must be nonempty.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Hence, it is a logical theorem of first-order logic that something exists – usually expressed as the assertion that something is identical to itself, $\exists x(x=x)$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Consequently, it is a theorem of every first-order theory that something exists.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] However, as noted above, because in the intended semantics of ZFC, there are only sets, the interpretation of this logical theorem in the context of ZFC is that some *set* exists.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Hence, there is no need for a separate axiom asserting that a set exists.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Second, however, even if ZFC is formulated in so-called free logic, in which it is not provable from logic alone that something exists, the axiom of infinity asserts that an *infinite* set exists.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] This implies that *a* set exists, and so, once again, it is superfluous to include an axiom asserting as much.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Two sets are equal (are the same set) if they have the same elements.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The converse of this axiom follows from the substitution property of equality.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] ZFC is constructed in first-order logic.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Some formulations of first-order logic include identity; others do not.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] which says that if x and y have the same elements, then they belong to the same sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Every non-empty set x contains a member y such that x and y are disjoint sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] With the axioms of pairing and union, this implies that no set is an element of itself.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] With the axioms of infinity, replacement, and union, this implies that every set has an ordinal rank.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Subsets are commonly constructed using set builder notation.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The axiom schema of specification states that this subset always exists (it is an axiom *schema* because there is one axiom for each $\varphi$ ).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Formally, let $\varphi$ be any formula in the language of ZFC with all free variables among $x,z,w_{1},\ldots ,w_{n}$ ( y is not free in $\varphi$ ).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] In some other axiomatizations of ZF, this axiom is redundant in that it follows from the axiom schema of replacement and the axiom of the empty set.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] On the other hand, the axiom schema of specification can be used to prove the existence of the empty set, denoted $\varnothing$ , once at least one set is known to exist.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] One way to do this is to use a property $\varphi$ which no set has.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Thus, the axiom of the empty set is implied by the nine axioms presented here.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The axiom of extensionality implies the empty set is unique (does not depend on w ).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] It is common to make a definitional extension that adds the symbol " $\varnothing$ " to the language of ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] If x and y are sets, then there exists a set which contains x and y as elements; for example, if $x=\{1,2\}$ and $y=\{2,3\}$ , then z might be $\{\{1,2\},\{2,3\}\}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The axiom schema of specification must be used to reduce this to a set with exactly these two elements.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The union over the elements of a set exists.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The axiom schema of replacement asserts that the image of a set under any definable function will also fall inside a set.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Formally, let $\varphi$ be any formula in the language of ZFC whose free variables are among $x,y,A,w_{1},\dotsc ,w_{n},$ so that in particular B is not free in $\varphi$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] In other words, if the relation $\varphi$ represents a definable function f , A represents its domain, and $f(x)$ is a set for every $x\in A,$ then the range of f is a subset of some set B .
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The form stated here, in which B may be larger than strictly necessary, is sometimes called the axiom schema of collection.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Let $S(w)$ abbreviate $w\cup \{w\},$ where w is some set.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] (We can see that $\{w\}$ is a valid set by applying the axiom of pairing with $x=y=w$ so that the set z is $\{w\}$ ).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Then there exists a set X such that the empty set $\varnothing$ , defined axiomatically, is a member of X and, whenever a set y is a member of X then $S(y)$ is also a member of X.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] More colloquially, there exists a set X having infinitely many members.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] These members are built by repeatedly applying the operation S starting from the empty set.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Each result of this construction is distinct from the previous ones, so the process does not loop or repeat.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The minimal set X satisfying the axiom of infinity is the von Neumann ordinal ω, which can also be thought of as the set of natural numbers $\mathbb {N}$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Alternative forms of these axioms are often encountered, some of which are listed in Jech (2003).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Some ZF axiomatizations include an axiom asserting that the empty set exists.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The axioms of pairing, union, replacement, and power set are often stated so that the members of the set x whose existence is being asserted are just those sets which the axiom asserts x must contain.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The last axiom, commonly known as the axiom of choice, is presented here as a property about well-orders, as in Kunen (1980).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] For any set X , there exists a binary relation R which well-orders X .
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] This means R is a linear order on X such that every nonempty subset of X has a least element under the order R .
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Given axioms 1–8, many statements are provably equivalent to axiom 9.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The most common of these goes as follows.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Let X be a set whose members are all nonempty.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Then there exists a function f from X to the union of the members of X , called a "choice function", such that for all $Y\in X$ one has $f(Y)\in Y$ .
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] A third version of the axiom, also equivalent, is Zorn's lemma.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Since the existence of a choice function when X is a finite set is easily proved from axioms *1–8*, AC only matters for certain infinite sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] AC is characterized as nonconstructive because it asserts the existence of a choice function but says nothing about how this choice function is to be "constructed".
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] One motivation for the ZFC axioms is the cumulative hierarchy of sets introduced by John von Neumann.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] In this viewpoint, the universe of set theory is built up in stages, with one stage for each ordinal number.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] At each following stage, a set is added to the universe if all of its elements have been added at previous stages.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Thus the empty set is added at stage 1, and the set containing the empty set is added at stage 2.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The collection of all sets that are obtained in this way, over all the stages, is known as *V*.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The sets in *V* can be arranged into a hierarchy by assigning to each set the first stage at which that set was added to *V*.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] It is provable that a set is in *V* if and only if the set is pure and well-founded.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] And *V* satisfies all the axioms of ZFC if the class of ordinals has appropriate reflection properties.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] For example, suppose that a set *x* is added at stage α, which means that every element of *x* was added at a stage earlier than α.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Then, every subset of *x* is also added at (or before) stage α, because all elements of any subset of *x* were also added before stage α.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] This means that any subset of *x* which the axiom of separation can construct is added at (or before) stage α, and that the powerset of *x* will be added at the next stage after α.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The picture of the universe of sets stratified into the cumulative hierarchy is characteristic of ZFC and related axiomatic set theories such as Von Neumann–Bernays–Gödel set theory (often called NBG) and Morse–Kelley set theory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The cumulative hierarchy is not compatible with other set theories such as New Foundations.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] It is possible to change the definition of *V* so that at each stage, instead of adding all the subsets of the union of the previous stages, subsets are only added if they are definable in a certain sense.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] This results in a more "narrow" hierarchy, which gives the constructible universe *L*, which also satisfies all the axioms of ZFC, including the axiom of choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] It is independent from the ZFC axioms whether *V* = *L*.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Although the structure of *L* is more regular and well behaved than that of *V*, few mathematicians argue that *V* = *L* should be added to ZFC as an additional "axiom of constructibility".
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Proper classes (collections of mathematical objects defined by a property shared by their members which are too big to be sets) can only be treated indirectly in ZF (and thus ZFC).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] An alternative to proper classes while staying within ZF and ZFC is the *virtual class* notational construct introduced by Quine (1969), where the entire construct *y* ∈ { *x* | F*x* } is simply defined as F*y*.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] This provides a simple notation for classes that can contain sets but need not themselves be sets, while not committing to the ontology of classes (because the notation can be syntactically converted to one that only uses sets).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Quine's approach built on the earlier approach of Bernays & Fraenkel (1958).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Virtual classes are also used in Levy (2002), Takeuti & Zaring (1982), and in the Metamath implementation of ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The axiom schemata of replacement and separation each contain infinitely many instances.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Montague (1961) included a result first proved in his 1957 Ph.D. thesis: if ZFC is consistent, it is impossible to axiomatize ZFC using only finitely many axioms.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] On the other hand, von Neumann–Bernays–Gödel set theory (NBG) can be finitely axiomatized.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The ontology of NBG includes proper classes as well as sets; a set is any class that can be a member of another class.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] NBG and ZFC are equivalent set theories in the sense that any theorem not mentioning classes and provable in one theory can be proved in the other.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Gödel's second incompleteness theorem says that a recursively axiomatizable system that can interpret Robinson arithmetic can prove its own consistency only if it is inconsistent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Moreover, Robinson arithmetic can be interpreted in general set theory, a small fragment of ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Hence the consistency of ZFC cannot be proved within ZFC itself (unless it is actually inconsistent).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Thus, to the extent that ZFC is identified with ordinary mathematics, the consistency of ZFC cannot be demonstrated in ordinary mathematics.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The consistency of ZFC does follow from the existence of a weakly inaccessible cardinal, which is unprovable in ZFC if ZFC is consistent.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Nevertheless, it is deemed unlikely that ZFC harbors an unsuspected contradiction; it is widely believed that if ZFC were inconsistent, that fact would have been uncovered by now.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] ZFC does not contain the classic paradoxes of naive set theory: Russell's paradox, the Burali-Forti paradox, and Cantor's paradox.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Abian & LaMacchia (1978) studied a subtheory of ZFC consisting of the axioms of extensionality, union, powerset, replacement, and choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Using models, they proved this subtheory consistent, and proved that each of the axioms of extensionality, replacement, and power set is independent of the four remaining axioms of this subtheory.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] If this subtheory is augmented with the axiom of infinity, each of the axioms of union, choice, and infinity is independent of the five remaining axioms.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Because there are non-well-founded models that satisfy each axiom of ZFC except the axiom of regularity, that axiom is independent of the other ZFC axioms.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] If consistent, ZFC cannot prove the existence of the inaccessible cardinals that category theory requires.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Huge sets of this nature are possible if ZF is augmented with Tarski's axiom.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Assuming that axiom turns the axioms of infinity, power set, and choice (7–9 above) into theorems.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Many important statements are independent of ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The independence is usually proved by forcing, whereby it is shown that every countable transitive model of ZFC (sometimes augmented with large cardinal axioms) can be expanded to satisfy the statement in question.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] A different expansion is then shown to satisfy the negation of the statement.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] An independence proof by forcing automatically proves independence from arithmetical statements, other concrete statements, and large cardinal axioms.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Some statements independent of ZFC can be proven to hold in particular inner models, such as in the constructible universe.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] However, some statements that are true about constructible sets are not consistent with hypothesized large cardinal axioms.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] A variation on the method of forcing can also be used to demonstrate the consistency and unprovability of the axiom of choice, i.e., that the axiom of choice is independent of ZF.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The consistency of choice can be (relatively) easily verified by proving that the inner model L satisfies choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] (Thus every model of ZF contains a submodel of ZFC, so that Con(ZF) implies Con(ZFC).) Since forcing preserves choice, we cannot directly produce a model contradicting choice from a model satisfying choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] However, we can use forcing to create a model which contains a suitable submodel, namely one satisfying ZF but not C.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Another method of proving independence results, one owing nothing to forcing, is based on Gödel's second incompleteness theorem.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] This approach employs the statement whose independence is being examined, to prove the existence of a set model of ZFC, in which case Con(ZFC) is true.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Since ZFC satisfies the conditions of Gödel's second theorem, the consistency of ZFC is unprovable in ZFC (provided that ZFC is, in fact, consistent).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Hence no statement allowing such a proof can be proved in ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] This method can prove that the existence of large cardinals is not provable in ZFC, but cannot prove that assuming such cardinals, given ZFC, is free of contradiction.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The project to unify set theorists behind additional axioms to resolve the continuum hypothesis or other meta-mathematical ambiguities is sometimes known as "Gödel's program".
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] ZFC has been criticized both for being excessively strong and for being excessively weak, as well as for its failure to capture objects such as proper classes.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Many mathematical theorems can be proven in much weaker systems than ZFC, such as Peano arithmetic and second-order arithmetic (as explored by the program of reverse mathematics).
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Saunders Mac Lane and Solomon Feferman have both made this point.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Some of "mainstream mathematics" (mathematics not directly connected with axiomatic set theory) is beyond Peano arithmetic and second-order arithmetic, but still, all such mathematics can be carried out in ZC (Zermelo set theory with choice), another theory weaker than ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Much of the power of ZFC, including the axiom of regularity and the axiom schema of replacement, is included primarily to facilitate the study of the set theory itself.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] On the other hand, among axiomatic set theories, ZFC is comparatively weak.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Unlike New Foundations, ZFC does not admit the existence of a universal set.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Hence the universe of sets under ZFC is not closed under the elementary operations of the algebra of sets.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Unlike von Neumann–Bernays–Gödel set theory (NBG) and Morse–Kelley set theory (MK), ZFC does not admit the existence of proper classes.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] A further comparative weakness of ZFC is that the axiom of choice included in ZFC is weaker than the axiom of global choice included in NBG and MK.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] There are numerous mathematical statements independent of ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] These include the continuum hypothesis, the Whitehead problem, and the normal Moore space conjecture.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Some of these conjectures are provable with the addition of axioms such as Martin's axiom or large cardinal axioms to ZFC.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] Some others are decided in ZF+AD where AD is the axiom of determinacy, a strong supposition incompatible with choice.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] One attraction of large cardinal axioms is that they enable many results from ZF+AD to be established in ZFC adjoined by some large cardinal axiom.
[src:forcing-set-theory/zermelo-fraenkel-set-theory] The Mizar system and metamath have adopted Tarski–Grothendieck set theory, an extension of ZFC, so that proofs involving Grothendieck universes (encountered in category theory and algebraic geometry) can be formalized.
